    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Victoria Santa Cruz (1922–2014) is one of the most influential figures in Afro-Peruvian cultural history. A choreographer, composer, and intellectual, Santa Cruz played a central role in the revival and revaluation of Afro-Peruvian culture in the twentieth century. At a time when Blackness was marginalized or reduced to stereotypes within Peruvian society, her work insisted on the dignity, complexity, and centrality of Afro-Peruvian identity."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "Santa Cruz approached art not simply as performance, but as a form of knowledge. For her, the body was a site where history, memory, and identity. Through rhythm, movement, and voice, she developed a practice that sought to reconnect Afro-Peruvian people with ancestral forms of expression that had been suppressed or devalued. Her work emphasized the importance of rhythm as a fundamental element of being, something that is not only heard, but felt and embodied."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "image",
      "url": "data:image/jpeg;base64,",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": "This perspective is powerfully articulated in her well-known poem "
        },
        {
          "text": "\"Me gritaron negra,\" i",
          "italic": true
        },
        {
          "text": "n which she recounts an experience of racial discrimination and traces a journey from internalized shame"
        },
        {
          "italic": true,
          "text": " to the "
        },
        {
          "text": "affirmation of Black identity. The poem moves from the violence of being called “negra” as an insult to reclaiming the term as a source of pride and strength. In doing so, Santa Cruz transforms language, memory, and emotion into a collective statement about Black consciousness and resistance.\n"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "children": [
        {
          "text": ""
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "uuid": "a683e47e-45ff-4b36-9221-6fb9629ffc64",
